  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Here are some of the key ones:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988 Vienna Convention):** This convention was one of the first major international agreements to address money laundering. It requires states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from drug trafficking and to cooperate in international investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000 Palermo Convention):** This convention expands the scope of money laundering offenses to include proceeds from a wider range of crimes, including organized crime. It also promotes international cooperation in asset recovery.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003 Merida Convention):** This convention focuses on combating corruption and includes provisions on preventing and combating money laundering related to corruption.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** While not a treaty or convention, the FATF Recommendations are the primary international standard for anti-money laundering and counter-terrorist financing (AML/CFT). The FATF is an inter-governmental body that develops and promotes policies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing. Its recommendations are widely adopted by countries around the world.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990 Strasbourg Convention) and its revised version:** This convention focuses on international cooperation in combating money laundering, including measures for identifying, tracing, freezing, seizing, and confiscating the proceeds of crime.\n\n*   **European Union Directives:** The European Union has also issued several directives on anti-money laundering, which set minimum standards for member states. These directives have been updated over time to reflect evolving threats and international standards.\n\nThese international laws and conventions provide a framework for countries to criminalize money laundering, implement preventative measures, and cooperate with each other in investigating and prosecuting money laundering offenses. However, enforcement and implementation of these laws can vary across countries.",
